Suggested Project Structure
1. Sales & Revenue Exploration

Goal:
Understand where money comes from.

Questions:

Which customers generate the most revenue?
Which product categories sell best?
How does revenue change over time?
Are there seasonal patterns?

Queries:

Top customers by revenue
Monthly revenue trend
Revenue by category
Top-selling products

Potential observations:

Revenue concentrated among a small customer segment
Some categories consistently outperform others
Sales fluctuate seasonally

Good beginner SQL skills here:

JOIN
GROUP BY
aggregates
date extraction
window functions later (OVER() lurking in swamp fog 🌫️)
2. Operations & Logistics

Goal:
Look for inefficiencies.

Questions:

How long do shipments take?
Which shippers are fastest/slowest?
Are some products rarely sold?
Which suppliers dominate inventory?

Queries:

Shipping delay analysis
Average fulfillment time
Products with low order frequency
Supplier contribution analysis

Potential observations:

Shipping performance differs between carriers
Some products contribute little activity
Inventory distribution may be uneven

This section feels “businessy” without pretending you solved global supply chains.

3. Employee & Territory Performance

Goal:
Compare workload and sales contribution.

Questions:

Which employees process most orders?
Which employees generate most revenue?
Are workloads balanced?
Which regions perform best?

Queries:

Orders per employee
Revenue by employee
Revenue by region/country

Potential observations:

Sales are concentrated among a few employees
Geographic performance differs significantly
Additional staffing/context data would be needed for conclusions

That disclaimer part is important. Real analysts constantly say:

“Data suggests X, but causation unclear.”

People trust cautious analysts more than LinkedIn prophets.

4. Customer Behavior & Product Patterns

Goal:
Understand purchasing behavior.

Questions:

Which products are bought together?
Which customers became inactive?
Which customers order frequently?
What are common reorder patterns?

Queries:

Product pair analysis
Inactive customers
Repeat purchase frequency
Average basket size

Potential observations:

Certain product combinations recur frequently
Some customers may be at churn risk
Bundling opportunities may exist

Tiny proto-Amazon larva wriggles into existence 🐛📦

Then End With
5. Limitations

This section is underrated and actually makes projects look smarter.

Example:

Dataset is synthetic and relatively small
No true inventory stock levels
No marketing/customer demographic data
Revenue calculated from order details only
Employee performance lacks staffing/hour context

That instantly makes the project look more mature.
